\paragraph{Hero summary.}
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_two_period} is the single-figure summary: data
reco vs reweighted MC reco overlaid for both periods, residuals, the
recovered $w(z)$, and the headline numbers of
Table~\ref{tab:iter_summary}. The 0\,mrad mix-MC matches data to
$\sim\!1\,\%$ per bin throughout the closure window; the 1.5\,mrad mix
matches to $\sim\!1$--$2\,\%$ in the bulk and degrades to $\sim\!15\,\%$
only in the handful of bins right at the closure-window edge
$|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_two_period.pdf}
\caption{Iterative data-driven reweight summary, both crossing angles.
Top row: data reco (black) vs mixed MC reco after iterative reweight
(red) for 1.5\,mrad and 0\,mrad. Middle row: residual
$r(z)\!=\!D/M_\mathrm{iter}$ inside the closure window (vertical
dashed lines). Bottom row: recovered $w(z)$, with the seed Gaussian
overlaid for context. The 0\,mrad case is essentially closed; the
1.5\,mrad case is closed in the bulk and stalls at the closure-window
edge (see Section~\ref{sec:iter:interpretation}).}
\label{fig:iter_two_period}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{0\,mrad: clean convergence.}
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_0mrad_closure} shows the 6-panel diagnostic for
0\,mrad. The seed Gaussian with $\sigma_\mathrm{seed}\!\simeq\!54$\,cm
already captures most of the shape (initial $\max|r-1|\!=\!8\,\%$,
initial $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!\simeq\!467$); the iteration cleans up
the residual over 7 updates and drops below the 1\,\% tolerance at
iteration 6. The recovered $w(z)$ is smooth and broadly Gaussian, with
a small enhancement of the central core relative to the seed --- this
is consistent with the data luminous region being slightly more peaked
than a single Gaussian. A stat-only pull diagnostic is written to the
fit output directory (\texttt{output/0mrad/pull\_distribution.pdf}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_0mrad_closure.pdf}
\caption{0\,mrad iterative closure (6 panels). Top-left: data reco
vs mixed MC reco after iteration. Top-middle: residual inside the
closure window. Top-right: recovered $w(z)$ vs seed Gaussian.
Bottom-left: per-iteration $\max|r-1|$ trajectory. Bottom-middle:
per-iteration $\chi^2$. Bottom-right: comparison of the iterative
reweight to no-reweight, parametric Gaussian (stage 1), and stage 1+2.
The iterative method reaches the 1\,\% per-bin tolerance at
iteration 6, after a total of 7 iterations (the tolerance is checked
at the end of each update).}
\label{fig:iter_0mrad_closure}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{1.5\,mrad: bulk closure, edge stall.}
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_1p5mrad_closure} shows the 6-panel diagnostic for
1.5\,mrad. The story is qualitatively different. The seed Gaussian
with $\sigma_\mathrm{seed}\!\simeq\!21$\,cm starts from
$\max|r-1|\!=\!63\,\%$ and an in-window $\chi^2$ of $1.4\!\times\!10^6$;
the first $\sim\!5$ iterations make dramatic progress, then the
iteration enters a slow plateau driven by a small cluster of bins at
the closure-window edge $|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm (one dominant, one or
two others close behind). After 30 iterations, $\chi^2$ in the window
has dropped by $2060\times$ to 689 (in-window
$\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!=\!20.9$, ndf 33), but $\max|r-1|$ sits at
$0.15$, set by those stuck edge bins. Inside the bulk
$|z|\!<\!60$\,cm closure is at the $\sim\!1$--$2\,\%$ level on every
bin --- see the residual panel of Figure~\ref{fig:iter_1p5mrad_closure}.
The recovered $w(z)$ shows a strong central core boost
($w(0)\!\simeq\!8$), a mid-$z$ dip, and a clear $\pm$ asymmetry in the
$|z|\!\simeq\!40$--$60$\,cm region that no symmetric Gaussian ansatz can
represent.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_1p5mrad_closure.pdf}
\caption{1.5\,mrad iterative closure (6 panels). Same layout as
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_0mrad_closure}. The bulk of the residual closes
to $\sim\!1$--$2\,\%$ inside $|z|\!<\!60$\,cm; the iteration stalls on
a small cluster of bins at the closure-window edge
$|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm where the double-interaction MBD resolution
kernel starts to dominate the bin content
(Section~\ref{sec:iter:interpretation}). The recovered $w(z)$
in the top-right panel shows a central core boost, a mid-$z$ dip, and
a clear $\pm$ asymmetry in the $|z|\!\simeq\!40$--$60$\,cm region that
no symmetric Gaussian ansatz can represent.}
\label{fig:iter_1p5mrad_closure}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:iter_1p5mrad_convergence} shows the convergence
trajectory in detail: $\max|r-1|$ and $\chi^2$ as a function of
iteration, on a log-log scale. The two curves track the same physical
story --- a fast power-law drop for the first $\sim\!5$ updates, then a
near-flat plateau where each additional iteration moves $\chi^2$ by
$\lesssim 1\,\%$.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_1p5mrad_convergence.pdf}
\caption{1.5\,mrad convergence trajectory: $\max|r-1|$ in the closure
window (top) and in-window $\chi^2$ (bottom) as a function of iteration.
The iteration makes dramatic progress in the first 4--5 updates, then
enters a plateau where a small cluster of stuck edge bins near
$|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm prevents further $\max|r-1|$ progress. The
30-iteration cap is hit without reaching the 1\,\% convergence
tolerance.}
\label{fig:iter_1p5mrad_convergence}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Method comparison.}
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_0mrad_methods} shows the four reweight methods
ranked on the 0\,mrad mix: no reweight, parametric Gaussian
(\emph{stage 1}, equivalent to the closed-form 2D Gaussian of
Section~\ref{sec:proposal} restricted to a single-parameter $\sigma$
fit on the truth axis), parametric plus residual correction
(\emph{stage 2}), and the iterative method. The ordering is
\begin{equation*}
\text{iterative} \;<\; \text{stage 1+2} \;<\; \text{stage 1} \;<\; \text{no reweight},
\end{equation*}
with each step bringing measurable improvement. The analogous plot at
1.5\,mrad is Figure~\ref{fig:iter_1p5mrad_methods}: the same ordering
holds but with much larger gaps between the methods --- the parametric
stage 1 alone gives $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!\simeq\!3237$ in the closure
window, and the iterative reweight brings it down to 20.9, a
$\sim\!155\times$
improvement on top of the parametric fit.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_0mrad_methods.pdf}
\caption{Method comparison at 0\,mrad: data reco vs mixed MC reco under
no reweight (gray), parametric Gaussian stage 1 (blue), parametric plus
residual stage 2 (green), and the iterative data-driven reweight (red).
Ratio panel below. The iterative method is the closest match across
the closure window; all four agree at the 1--2\,\% level inside the
bulk, with the parametric stages diverging mildly at $|z|\!\gtrsim\!100$\,cm.}
\label{fig:iter_0mrad_methods}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{figures/vertex_reweight_iter_1p5mrad_methods.pdf}
\caption{Method comparison at 1.5\,mrad, same layout as
Figure~\ref{fig:iter_0mrad_methods}. The spread between methods is
much larger here. Stage 1 (blue) has a visible +50\,cm bump in the
ratio panel and a global $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!\simeq\!3237$; stage 1+2
(green) reduces the bump partially but still leaves $\sim\!60\,\%$
residuals at the edges; the iterative method (red) closes the bulk
$|z|\!<\!60$\,cm to $1$--$2\,\%$ and stalls only at the edge. The
headline number is the $\sim\!155\times$ in-window $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}$
improvement from stage 1 to iterative.}
\label{fig:iter_1p5mrad_methods}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Physics interpretation}
\label{sec:iter:interpretation}

\paragraph{Why 0\,mrad is easy.}
At 0\,mrad the beams overlap head-on along their full length and the
luminous region is broad ($\sigma_\mathrm{lum}\!\simeq\!54$\,cm),
nearly equal to the generator beam profile
($\sigma_\mathrm{gen}\!\simeq\!65$\,cm). The shape of the data
reco vertex is also close to a single Gaussian. The seed Gaussian is
therefore already a good first approximation, the initial residual is
$\sim\!8\,\%$, and the iteration just cleans up small departures
(slightly enhanced central core). Convergence in a handful of
iterations is what one would expect from a near-textbook
deconvolution problem.

\paragraph{Why 1.5\,mrad is hard.}
At 1.5\,mrad three things conspire:
\begin{itemize}\setlength\itemsep{2pt}
\item The Piwinski crossing-angle effect compresses the luminous region
to $\sigma_\mathrm{lum}\!\simeq\!21$\,cm, almost a factor of three
narrower than the generator profile. The reweight has to extract a
narrow target from a wide source, and the dynamic range of $w(z)$ at
the central core is correspondingly large
($w(0)\!\simeq\!8$).
\item The data reco distribution is \emph{not} a clean Gaussian. It has
a narrow core plus a $\pm$-asymmetric mid-tail bump near
$|z_r|\!\simeq\!45$--$60$\,cm. The iterative method discovers this
asymmetry directly --- the recovered $w(z)$ is asymmetric in the same
$z$ range --- whereas a single-parameter Gaussian (the existing
report's stage 1, equivalent to the closed-form 2D Gaussian fit of
Section~\ref{sec:proposal}) cannot represent it. This is exactly why
stage 1 alone gives $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!\simeq\!3237$ on the
1.5\,mrad mix, and why the iterative method drops it to $\simeq\!21$.
\item The MBD resolution tail leak from core-truth events fills the
bins near the closure-window edge ($|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm), and the
iteration becomes insensitive to $w(z)$ updates at that $z$:
contributions to those bins come dominantly from \emph{other}
truth-$z$ values via the wide double-interaction reco-truth kernel.
The iteration has the wrong handle on those bins, and that is what
sets the residual floor at $\max|r-1|\!\simeq\!15\,\%$.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{What the recovered $w(z)$ looks like.}
At 1.5\,mrad, $w(z)$ has three distinguishing features visible in the
top-right panel of Figure~\ref{fig:iter_1p5mrad_closure}:
(a) a strong central peak with $w(0)\!\simeq\!8$ that pulls
double-interaction events whose truth vertices lie close to the IP
into the data-like core; (b) a mid-$z$ dip that suppresses the
generator's natural $|z|\!\sim\!30$--$50$\,cm population to match the
narrow data core; and (c) a clear $\pm$ asymmetry in
$|z|\!\simeq\!40$--$60$\,cm tracking the asymmetric mid-tail bump in
the data. None of these features is representable by a symmetric
single-parameter Gaussian. The 2D Gaussian proposal of
Section~\ref{sec:proposal} captures (a) and (b) implicitly through
the closed-form ratio of Gaussians, but cannot represent (c). At
0\,mrad, $w(z)$ is essentially the seed Gaussian with a small central
enhancement, and the symmetric Gaussian ansatz is a good
approximation.

\paragraph{Relationship to the 2D Gaussian proposal.}
The iterative method is a direct generalization of the 2D Gaussian
proposal (Section~\ref{sec:proposal}). Both use the factorization
$w(z_{t,1})\,w(z_{t,2})$ for double-interaction events that comes from
the algebraic argument of Section~\ref{sec:toy_decomposition}, both
operate on truth vertices, and both close all three vertex axes
(primary truth, secondary truth, reco) by construction. The difference
is that the 2D Gaussian assumes a closed-form Gaussian ratio with
$(\sigma_\mathrm{MC}, \sigma_\mathrm{lum})$ taken as scalar inputs,
while the iterative method discovers $w(z)$ on the bin grid from the
data. When the data luminous region is well approximated by a single
Gaussian, the iterative $w(z)$ \emph{reduces} to the 2D Gaussian form
(the seed already does most of the work; iterations are small
corrections, as seen at 0\,mrad). When the data is not Gaussian, the
iterative method generalizes naturally and the closed-form proposal
does not.

\paragraph{Why parametric stage 1 fails at 1.5\,mrad.}
The single-parameter Gaussian ansatz has only $\sigma_\mathrm{tgt}$
to play with. It can match the central core (by setting
$\sigma_\mathrm{tgt}\!\sim\!16$\,cm, which is the data-fitted value
that minimizes the global $\chi^2$) or the tails (by setting it
larger), but not both. With the data showing a narrow core
$+$ a non-Gaussian mid-tail bump, the best-fit single Gaussian is
incompatible with the bin-by-bin shape at the few-tens-of-percent
level: $\chi^2/\mathrm{ndf}\!\simeq\!3237$ in the closure window. Adding
the parametric residual correction (stage 2) reduces this substantially
but still leaves $\sim\!60\,\%$ residuals. The iterative method, with
80 free parameters (one $w$ per bin, smoothed and damped to suppress
overfitting), finally captures the actual data shape.

\subsection{Caveats and next steps}
\label{sec:iter:caveats}

\paragraph{(i) photon10-only mix.}
The current fit uses photon10 + photon10\_double only. The full
production blend also includes jet12 + jet12\_double (jet sample
weights, finer truth $z$ shape on the jet side). Extending the fit to
all four samples is the obvious next step; mechanically it is two more
\texttt{load\_sample} calls plus the appropriate
cluster-weighted blend, but the closure numbers will move and should
be remeasured before any production hookup.

\paragraph{(ii) 1.5\,mrad did not fully converge.}
The 30-iteration cap was hit. Two questions are open: (a) whether
extending to $\sim\!100$ iterations would push the stuck edge bin to
convergence or whether it really is a hard physical floor (the
suspicion is the latter, because the stuck bin sits where the
double-interaction MBD reco-truth kernel dominates); and (b) whether
the failure to converge in $\max|r-1|$ matters for the downstream
analysis. The latter question has a fairly clean answer: the PPG12
analysis applies a fiducial cut $|z|\!<\!60$\,cm on both the reco and
truth vertex (Section~\ref{sec:xsec_impact}), and inside that cut the
per-bin closure is already at the 1--2\,\% level. The stuck edge bin
at $|z|\!\simeq\!83$\,cm is well outside the analysis fiducial. The
iteration is therefore good enough for the analysis use case, even
though it is not formally converged on the full closure-window
metric.

\paragraph{(iii) Downstream hookup is not done here.}
The output \texttt{reweight.root} histograms
(\texttt{h\_w\_iterative}, \texttt{h\_w\_seed},
\texttt{h\_M\_iterative}) are written and ready to be consumed by
\texttt{efficiencytool/RecoEffCalculator\_TTreeReader.C} and
\texttt{ShowerShapeCheck.C}, but the C++ side has not been touched yet.
The hookup is the same shape as the 2D Gaussian proposal hookup of
Section~\ref{sec:proposal}: read $w(z)$ from the ROOT file and apply it
to the per-event MC weight, with double-interaction events getting
$w(z_{t,1})\,w(z_{t,2})$. This requires the same
\texttt{vertexz\_truth\_second} branch from the staged
\texttt{CaloAna24.cc} patch to access the secondary truth vertex.

\paragraph{(iv) Implementation can be sped up.}
The current iteration rebuilds the MC reco histogram from scratch on
each pass, which is $\mathcal{O}(N_\mathrm{events})$ per iteration.
Precomputing $z^2$ and dropping the per-trial mask rebuild are
obvious optimizations and would give a $\sim\!10\times$ speedup with no
change in result. Not a blocker; just nice-to-have for the
all-samples extension.

\paragraph{(v) Relation to the ``Final recommendation''.}
The ``Final recommendation'' of Section~\ref{sec:why_matters} proposed
the closed-form 2D Gaussian as the method of choice. The iterative
data-driven method described here is a direct generalization: at
0\,mrad the two methods agree (and the iterative $w(z)$ reduces to the
2D Gaussian form up to small central-core corrections), while at
1.5\,mrad the iterative method captures asymmetric structure that the
closed-form Gaussian cannot. The pragmatic recommendation is therefore
to use the closed-form 2D Gaussian as the default nominal for both
periods, and to use the iterative $w(z)$ from
\texttt{efficiencytool/truth\_vertex\_reweight/} as the 1.5\,mrad
systematic variant, taking the difference as a vertex-shape modeling
uncertainty. The final number should be quoted after the
all-samples mix is run.
